In [12]:
# Encode categorical variables
for col in cat_cols:
    unique_value = sorted(df[col].unique())
    encode_col = 'Encode_' + col
    if  unique_value==['No', 'Yes']: # Encode all variables with 'Yes' and 'No' only
        df[encode_col] = df[col].map(dict(Yes=1, No=0))
        df.drop(columns=col,inplace=True)
    elif unique_value==['Female', 'Male']: # Encode Gender variable
        df[encode_col] = df[col].map(dict(Female=1, Male=0))
        df.drop(columns=[col], inplace=True)
    elif unique_value==['Month-to-month', 'One year', 'Two year']: # Encode Contract variable as its values have a natural ordered relationship
        df[encode_col] = df[col].map({'Month-to-month': 1, 'One year': 2, 'Two year': 3})
        df.drop(columns=[col], inplace=True)
    else:
        print(col, ': ', unique_value)

4.1 Run Models

Reference: https://www.kaggle.com/esmaascioglu/predicting-good-bad-customers-for-credit-cards

In [23]:
# Generate a new dataset for logistic regression
log_df = new_df.copy()
In [24]:
# Split dataset in features and target variable
y = log_df['Encode_Churn']
X = log_df.drop(columns=['Encode_Churn'])

# Split X and y into training and testing sets
X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.25,random_state=0)
In [25]:
# Run 7 different logistic regression models
classifiers = {
    "LogisticRegression" : LogisticRegression(),
    "KNeighbors" : KNeighborsClassifier(),
    "SVC" : SVC(C = 0.8,
                        kernel='linear',
                        probability=True),
    "DecisionTree" : DecisionTreeClassifier(),
    "RandomForest" : RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=250,
                                                                        max_depth=12,
                                                                        min_samples_leaf=16),
    "XGBoost" : XGBClassifier(max_depth=12,
                                              n_estimators=250,
                                              min_child_weight=8, 
                                              subsample=0.8, 
                                              learning_rate =0.02,    
                                              seed=42),
    "CatBoost" : CatBoostClassifier(iterations=250,
                                                       learning_rate=0.2,
                                                       od_type='Iter',
                                                       verbose=25,
                                                       depth=16,
                                                       random_seed=42)
}

result_table = pd.DataFrame(columns=['classifiers','accuracy','presicion','recall','f1_score','fpr','tpr','auc'])

for key, classifier in classifiers.items():
    classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
    y_predict = classifier.predict(X_test)
    
    yproba = classifier.predict_proba(X_test)[::,1]
    
    fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test,  yproba)
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, yproba)
    
    conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_predict)
    
    result_table = result_table.append({'classifiers':key,
                                                            'accuracy':accuracy_score(y_test, y_predict),
                                                            'presicion':precision_score(y_test, y_predict, average='weighted'),
                                                            'recall':recall_score(y_test, y_predict, average='weighted'),
                                                            'f1_score':f1_score(y_test, y_predict, average='weighted'),
                                                            'fpr':fpr, 
                                                            'tpr':tpr, 
                                                            'auc':auc
                                                             }, ignore_index=True)
    
    log_df[key] = classifier.predict(X)
        
result_table.set_index('classifiers', inplace=True)

# Plot continuous variables
box_cols = ['Tenure', 'MonthlyCharges', 'TotalCharges']
churn_colors = ['#9FB3BF','#295E73']

for col in box_cols:
    f, axs = plt.subplots(ncols=3, figsize=(16, 3))
    sns.despine(f)
    
    sns.boxenplot(x=log_df['Encode_Churn'], y=log_df[col], palette=churn_colors, ax=axs[0]).set(title='Churn Variable')
    sns.boxenplot(x=log_df[min_accuracy_model], y=log_df[col], palette=churn_colors, ax=axs[1]).set(title='Minimal Accurate Model Prediction')
    sns.boxenplot(x=log_df[max_accuracy_model], y=log_df[col], palette=churn_colors, ax=axs[2]).set(title='Maximal Accurate Model Prediction')
    
    plt.show()
In [33]:
# Plot dummy variables
bar_cols = [ 'Encode_Contract', 'OnlineSecurity_No', 'PaymentMethod_Electronic check']

for col in bar_cols:
    # Count the records by groups
    chu_df = log_df.groupby([col, 'Encode_Churn']).size().unstack().fillna(0)
    min_df = log_df.groupby([col, min_accuracy_model]).size().unstack().fillna(0)
    max_df = log_df.groupby([col, max_accuracy_model]).size().unstack().fillna(0)

    # Plot stacked bar charts
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(ncols=3,figsize=(16,3))

    chu_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=churn_colors, ax=axes[0]).set(title='Churn Variable', ylabel='Count')
    min_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=churn_colors, ax=axes[1]).set(title='Minimal Accurate Model Prediction')
    max_df.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, color=churn_colors, ax=axes[2]).set(title='Maximal Accurate Model Prediction')
    
    # Format plots
    fig.autofmt_xdate(rotation=0)

    plt.show()

5.2 Clustering Model 1

In [36]:
SSE = []

for cluster in range(1,10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_jobs = -1, n_clusters = cluster, init='k-means++')
    kmeans.fit(scaled_feature_df)
    SSE.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Convert the results into a dataframe and plotting them
frame = pd.DataFrame({'Cluster':range(1,10), 'SSE':SSE})
plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.plot(frame['Cluster'], frame['SSE'], marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')

# From the above chart, the first two PCA components explain about 80% of the variance in the dataset
# Rebuild the model with the first two components
ks = range(1, 10)
inertias = []

for k in ks:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k)
    model.fit(PCA_components.iloc[:,:2])
    inertias.append(model.inertia_)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
plt.plot(ks, inertias, '-o')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters, K')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.xticks(ks)
plt.show()
